      "id": 1,
      "text": "Harbor Bluffs was first homesteaded in 1856 by Moses Powledge, a Georgia native, on a bluff overlooking the Intracoastal.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        2,
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.harborbluffsneighborhood.com/history.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The area survived the 1894-95 and 1898 freezes thanks to Bayly's citrus trees, which later supplied budwood to growers nationwide.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18,
        19
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://largohistoricalsociety.org/harbor-bluffs-on-the-waters-edge/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Bayly's mansion and fishing shacks were the only structures until the turn of the century, when a New Zealand native named Phillip Bayly bought the land in 1883.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        17
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://largohistoricalsociety.org/harbor-bluffs-on-the-waters-edge/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "After WWII, investors bought 236 acres but left it undeveloped until 1953 when the Harbor Bluffs Development Corporation began building the first homes.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        26,
        27
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
